 and important, their clients are often socially important institutions (pe=
nsion funds etc.), the SEC=E2=80=99s job is to protect those clients, and s=
o the SEC should have more comprehensive rules about private funds=E2=80=99=
 practices. Those private funds should have to give their clients standardi=
zed regular financial disclosures, like public funds do; there should be ru=
les restricting their conflicts of interest and fees and generally protecti=
ng their clients. The rules would be=C2=A0less=C2=A0restrictive than the ru=
les for public mutual funds, because the private investors are more sophist=
icated, but they=E2=80=99d be similar in kind. The SEC=E2=80=99s job is to =
protect all investors, and if private equity investors aren=E2=80=99t doing=
 a good job of protecting themselves the SEC will.That was, I think, a very=
 aggressive interpretation of the SEC=E2=80=99s mandate. Meanwhile, I wrote=
 in 2022 about another case in which the Fifth Circuit ruled that the SEC w=
as unconstitutional? I mean, that overstates the situation, but the Fifth C=
ircuit did take a pretty aggressive view of the constitutional limits on th=
e SEC=E2=80=99s power. I wrote:It used to be accepted as a routine matter t=
hat the SEC could make rules under a very broad grant of power from Congres=
s to regulate securities markets in the public interest.=C2=A0I am not sure=
 that is true anymore.Yeah, it=E2=80=99s not.
