emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">opening and closi=
ng auctions</a>, etc.),=C2=A0and you have to follow the exchange=E2=80=99s =
rules about shareholder voting, independent directors, board diversity, etc=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those rules are probably somewhat driven =
by market demand: Exchange listing standards are in part a way for investor=
s to coordinate and solve collective action problems; the exchanges make ru=
les that require companies to do what most investors want. But they=E2=80=
=99re not=C2=A0<em>entirely=C2=A0</em>market-driven, and it=E2=80=99s alway=
s possible that Nasdaq cares more about board diversity than a lot of inves=
tors do. So you can start a new exchange and attract listings from companie=
s that want to be public but don=E2=80=99t want to have diverse boards.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, I mean, that=E2=80=99s one story! My impre=
ssion is that it is=C2=A0<em>relatively=C2=A0</em>easy to start a new stock=
 exchange and=C2=A0<em>attract trading</em>, because every trader connects =
to every exchange. It seems much harder to=C2=A0<em>attract listings</em>, =
because going public is a big fraught scary undertaking for a company; you =
want it to go well, and that means listing on an exchange with a lot of exp=
erience and name recognition. LTSE has been around since 2017=C2=A0and has =
been an official national stock exchange since 2019; like TXSE, it was star=
ted with the purpose of being more CEO-friendly in its listing standards. I=
