bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0NeuBase would like to give the money back to its shareholders. It=
 works out to between 13 and 67 cents per share, or it did in April; it=E2=
=80=99s probably less now. It=E2=80=99s not amazing, but it=E2=80=99s somet=
hing, and after all it=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>the shareholders=E2=80=99 mone=
y. They own the company, so they get whatever cash is left.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Except they don=E2=80=99t just=C2=A0<em>get=C2=A0</em>it. =
The way it works is that NeuBase would like to go out of business properly,=
 by dissolving the company under Delaware law. The company dissolves, it ha=
s no further business or assets or liabilities or corporate existence, and =
as its last act on Earth it sends each shareholder a check for 13 cents or =
whatever.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To do that, though, NeuBase needs a sh=
areholder vote. Specifically, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/35613642.264315/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9=
kYXRhLzExNzMyODEvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDQ1MjA3L3RtMjQ5NTk3LTJfZGVmMTRhLmh0bSN0QU=
5C/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39f01a40" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Delaware law requires</a>=C2=
=A0that a majority of its shares of stock=C2=A0vote in favor of dissolution=
. If a majority of shares vote yes, then everyone gets the 13 cents and Neu=
Base disappears. If not, then NeuBase hangs around, an empty company with n=
o business, no traded stock, and just a dwindling pile of cash.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You see where this is going, right? Who do you think o=
wns shares of a basically defunct delisted speculative biopharmaceutical co=
mpany? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s holders list starts with the company=E2=80=99s f=
ormer chief executive officer, who=E2=80=99s got about 6.1%. A few hedge fu=
nds own small stakes, or did as of their last 13F filings, but Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s total holders list adds up to just 27.9% of the stock. Most of the =
stock is owned by retail investors. Retail investors do not vote. In partic=
ular, a retail investor who bought into a hot biopharma company back when i=
t was developing a promising gene editing platform is not now going to vote=
 on a proposal to dissolve the company and get back 13 cents. Every retail =
investor has better things to do than=C2=A0vote on dissolving NeuBase.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So poor NeuBase is in limbo. It <a href=3D"http=
